<h4>
    Gravitational and Inertial Mass
</h4>

<p>
    In physics class, whenever was say "mass", or we use the variable \( m \) in a formula,
    we actually mean one of two different variables, called
    <strong>gravitational mass</strong> and <strong>inertial mass</strong>.
    In the way that all of the formulas in this class are structured, gravitational and inertial mass
    are identical. However, it is still crucial to identify which type of mass is indicated by a particular formula.
</p>

<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Gravitational mass</strong> indicates how strongly
        a mass attracts other masses according to Newton's Law of gravitation.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Inertial mass</strong> indicates how strongly an object
        resists changes to its velocity.
    </li>
</ul>

