<h4>
    A Proof
</h4>

<p>
    An object is in <emph>free-fall</emph> when the only force acting on that
    object is gravity. The free-body diagram of an object in free-fall is given by:
</p>
<div id = 'freeFallFreeBody'></div>

<script>
    let freeBodyDiagram = fastFBD([['down','gravity']]);
    $("#freeFallFreeBody").append(freeBodyDiagram.drawCanvas(200));
</script>

<p>
    Because only one force acts on the object in free-fall, its net force is equal to that single force,
    and thus:
    $$
    \Sigma F = F_g.
    $$
    This means that, according to Newton's Second Law:
    $$
    \Sigma F = F_g = m a.
    $$
    The variable \( m \) in the formula above is given by inertial mass, so we will denote it \( m_i \):
    $$
    \Sigma F = F_g = m_i a.
    $$
</p>

<p>
    Newton's Law of Universal Gravitation states that
    $$
    F_g = \frac{G m_1 m_2}{d^2}.
    $$
    In this case, the force of gravity is the force that is attracting the object towards the planet it is on.
    Without loss of generality, we will assume that the object falling is object 1 and the planet is object 2.
    Allow \( m \) to indicate the mass of the object falling, \( M \) to indicate the mass of the planet,
    and \( R \) to indicate the radius of the planet. By arguments made in a <a href = '#'>previous pod</a>,
    the variable \( d \), or distance between the centers of masses of the object, is equal to the radius of the planet \( \).
    With these alterations, newton's Law of Universal Gravitation becomes:
    $$
    F_g = \frac{G m M}{R^2}.
    $$
    Note that in this variable \( m \) is the gravitational mass of the object, so we will denote it \( m_g \):
    $$
    F_g = \frac{G m_g M}{R^2}.
    $$
</p>

<p>
    Combining the formulas derived, we have
    $$
    \Sigma F = F_g = m_i a = \frac{G m_g M}{R^2}.
    $$
    Now, we know that the inertial mass \( m_i \) is equal to the gravitational mass \( m_g \),
    this, these two variables cancel, and we have:
    $$
    \require{cancel}
    \cancel{m_i} a = \frac{G \cancel{m_g} M}{R^2},
    $$
    and thus:
    $$
    a = \frac{G M}{R^2}.
    $$
    As stated at the beginning of this pod, the object above is in free-fall,
    and the free-fall acceleration on a planet is given by the variable \( g \),
    thus we have:
    $$
    g = \frac{G M}{R^2}.
    $$
</p>

<p>
    Does the above formula connect with the physics that we know?
    We know that all objects of any mass have the same free-fall acceleration on each planet.
    The formula above includes <emph>only</emph> qualities of the planet (its mass and radius),
    and no qualities of the object. These canceled out because inertial and gravitational mass are equal.
    Thus, the formula derived is consistent with the physics we know and observe.
</p>

<h4>
    The force formula
</h4>

<p>
    In the <a href = '/unit/dynamics/quantitative_dynamics'>unit on quantitative dynamics</a>,
    we solved many different
    problems, particularly involving <a href = '/pod/169d20af-4f7b-417e-b6c8-1a772ff24d05'>blocks</a>
    and <a href = '/pod/169d20af-4f7b-417e-b6c8-1a772ff24d05'>elevators</a>.

    In each of these problems, gravity was one of the forces that we considered.
    We used a very simple formula for the magnitude of the force of gravity:
    \( F_g = mg \).
</p>

<p>
    Now, that we are exploring gravity more closely, we are learning a far more complicated formula
    for the force of gravity \( F_g = \frac{G m_1 m_2}{d^2} \).
    Why are there two formulas for gravity? How are we supposed to make sense of them both?
</p>

<p>
    The formula \( F_g = mg \) can actually be derived from the formula \( F_g = \frac{G m_1 m_2}{d^2} \)!
</p>

<h5>
    Derivation:
</h5>

<ul>
    <li>
        An object is located on the surface of a planet. The planet has mass \( M \)
        and radius \( R \), adn the object has a mass \( m \).
        The force of gravity between the object and the planet is given by the Universal Law of Gravitation:
        $$
        F_g = \frac{G m_1 m_2}{d^2} = \frac{m M}{R^2}
        $$
    </li>
    <li>
        This formula can be rearranged:
        $$
        F_g = \frac{G M}{R^2} \cdot m
        $$
    </li>
    <li>
        In the derivation of free-fall acceleration given above, we determined that all objects
        in free-fall on a given planet accelerate towards the ground at a rate \( g \), and that
        \( g \) is given by:
        $$
        g = \frac{G M}{R^2}
        $$
    </li>
    <li>
        Thus, we can substitute the equaiton for \( g \) into the equation for \( F_g \), and we find:
        $$
        F_g = \frac{G M}{R^2} \cdot m = g \cdot m
        $$
        or
        $$
        F_g = mg
        $$
    </li>
    <li>
        It is crucial to state clearly what this equation means.
        This equation only applies to an object located on the surface of a planet.
        \( F_g \) represents the force of gravity attracting that planet inwards (which we call "down").
        This value is also often called the <strong>weight</strong>.
        The variable \( m \) is the mass of the object and \( g \) is the free-fall acceleration,
        which is a property of the planet.
    </li>
</ul>

<p>
    Many physics textbooks derive the formula \( F_g = mg \) from the formula \( \Sigma F = ma \).
    The reasoning is that when an object is in free-fall, \( Sigma F = F_g \) and \( a = g \).
    However, this is not as rigorous an explanation as deriving \( F_g = mg \) from the law of universal gravitation.
    Newton's Second Law: \( \Sigma F = ma \), is a law that describes the relationship between forces
    and acceleration. It's purpose is not the describe the source of a force itself.
    The formula \( F_g = \frac{G m_1 m_2}{d^2} \), by contrast, is a formula that describes
    the source of the force of gravity.
    \( F_g = \frac{G m_1 m_2}{d^2} \), or the Law of Universal Gravitation, describes all gravitation,
    and \( F_g = mg \) describes one specific case of this: the force of gravity attracting a person
    to a planet on the surface of that planet.
</p>

<p>
    Furthermore, there is one other reason why \( F_g = mg \) is best seen in relation to the formula
    \( F_g = \frac{G m_1 m_2}{d^2} \).
    Both of these equations include the <emph>gravitational mass</emph> of an object, that is,
    the amount that it attracts other objects that have mass.
    The formula \( \Sigma F = ma \), by contrast, includes the <emph>inertial mass</emph> of an object,
    its resistance to changes in velocity. Even though gravitational mass and inertial mass are
    equal, we will understand physics best if we always keep track of which one we are working with!
</p>

